'''Richard Cordray''' (born May 3, 1959) is an American politician of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] who serves as the [[Attorney General of Ohio]].  Cordray was elected on November 4, 2008 to fill the remainder of the unexpired term ending January 2011. Prior to his election as Ohio Attorney General, Cordray served as the [[Ohio State Treasurer]] and as [[treasurer]] of [[Franklin County, Ohio]].  He has also previously served as a member of the [[Ohio House of Representatives]] (1991&ndash;1993) and as the first [[Solicitor General of Ohio|Ohio state solicitor]] (1993&ndash;1994). 

Cordray was a [[Marshall Scholar]] at [[University of Oxford|Oxford University]], 1981&ndash;83.  Later, he was editor-in-chief of the ''[[University of Chicago Law Review]]'' and subsequently served as a [[law clerk]] for the [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]]. In 1987 he became an undefeated five-time ''[[Jeopardy!]]'' champion.

After his seat in the Ohio House of Representatives was [[redistricting|redistricted]] in 1992, Cordray ran unsuccessfully that year for a [[United States House of Representatives]] seat. The following year he was appointed by the office of the Ohio attorney general as the first Ohio state solicitor. His experience as Solicitor has led to his arguing six cases before the United States Supreme Court, where he had previously clerked.  Following Republican victories in Ohio statewide elections in 1994, Cordray left his appointed position to pursue private practice of law before becoming Franklin County treasurer in 2002. While in private practice he made unsuccessful runs for Ohio attorney general in 1998  and [[United States Senate|United States senator]] in 2000.  Cordray won re-election as Franklin County treasurer before being elected state treasurer in 2006.

==Early life and education==
Cordray was raised in {{city-state|Grove City|Ohio}}, where he attended public schools. While attending [[Grove City High School (Grove City, Ohio)|Grove City High School]], Cordray became a champion on the high school quiz show ''In The Know'' and worked for [[minimum wage]] at [[McDonald's]].<ref name=FBfRC/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=11B869246CDD2B20&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Democrat's Campaign Appeal Crosses Party Lines In 33rd District|accessdate=2008-10-18|date=1990-11-01|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Yost, Mary}}</ref> He graduated from high school in 1977 as co-[[valedictorian]] of his class.<ref name=GSLG>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=11B95EF254F9DB98&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Graduates Say - Last Goodbye|accessdate=2008-10-17|date=1988-05-15|accessdate=Newsbank|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=}}</ref> His first job in politics was as an intern for [[United States Senator]] [[John Glenn]] as a junior at [[Michigan State University]]'s [[James Madison College]].<ref name=FBfRC/> Cordray earned [[Phi Beta Kappa]] honors and graduated [[summa cum laude]] with a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in Legal & Political Theory in 1981. As a [[Marshall Scholarship|Marshall Scholar]], he earned an [[Master of Arts (postgraduate)|MA]] with first class honours in [[Economics]] from the [[University of Oxford]] and earned a [[Blue (university sport)|Varsity Blue]] in basketball in 1983.<ref name=FBfRC/> At the [[University of Chicago Law School]], where he earned his [[Juris Doctor]] with honors in 1986, he served as editor-in-chief of the ''University of Chicago Law Review''.<ref name=FBfRC>{{cite web|url=http://www.smartvoter.org/2000/03/07/oh/state/vote/cordray_r/bio.html|title=Full Biography for Richard Cordray|accessdate=2008-10-15|date=2000-02-06|publisher=[[League of Women Voters]] of California Education Fund.}}</ref><ref name=STCLFLTHCCIRC/> After starting work as a [[law clerk]] at the [[U.S. Supreme Court]], he came back to his high school to deliver the [[commencement speech]] for the graduating class in 1988.<ref name=GSLG/>

==Career==
===Early legislative career===
Cordray began his career clerking for [[Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court associate justices]] [[Byron White]] and [[Anthony Kennedy]].<ref name=FBfRC/> After clerking for White in 1987&ndash;1988, he was hired by the international law firm [[Jones Day]] to work in their Cleveland office.<ref name=STCLFLTHCCIRC>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=11B95FDD2ABB3D50&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Supremely Trained - Columbus Law Firm Lures Two High-Court Clerks In Recruiting Coup|accessdate=2008-10-17|date=1988-10-26|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Fiely, Dennis}}</ref>

In 1990 Cordray ran for an Ohio State House of Representatives seat, in the 33rd District (southern and western [[Franklin County, Ohio|Franklin County]]), against six-term incumbent Republican Don Gilmore.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=11B8674FEDCACF10&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Democrats Pick Lawyer To Run Against Gilmore|accessdate=2008-10-17|date=1990-01-17|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Curtin, Mike}}</ref> Unopposed for the Democratic nomination,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=11B868266E218260&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Two Legislators Face Foes in County|accessdate=2008-10-17|date=1990-05-06|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Johnson, Alan}}</ref> he defeated Gilmore by a 18,573&ndash;11,944 (61&ndash;39%) margin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=11B8692BD861D240&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Ohio House of Representatives|accessdate=2008-10-18|date=1990-05-06|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]}}</ref> As a state representative from 1991 to 1992, Cordray legislated against crime, on behalf of the environment, and for the protection of children and families.<ref name=FBfRC/> He also taught various courses at [[The Ohio State University]] [[Moritz College of Law]] and at [[Georgetown University]].<ref name=FBfRC/>

In 1991 the state Apportionment Board, controlled by a 3&ndash;2 Republican majority despite the party's  61&ndash;38 minority in the state House of Representatives,<ref name=1SLTTOoO>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10E0D70FC69B8F10&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=130 State Legislators Take Their Oath of Office - Families, Friends Watch At Statehouse|accessdate=2008-10-18|date=1991-01-08|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Leonard, Lee}}</ref> redrew state legislative districts following the results of the [[1990 Census]], in the hope of retaking control of the state House.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10E0D86AF2DF4508&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Republicans Hope New Lines Will Help Win House Control|accessdate=2008-10-18|date=1991-10-03|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Plain Dealer (newspaper)|The Plain Dealer]]|author=Suddes, Thomas and Mary Beth Lane}}</ref> The new boundaries created nine  districts each with two resident incumbent Democrats, pairing Cordray with the twenty-two-year incumbent [[Michael Stinziano]].<ref name=RSLSTNH>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F80340D663543B7&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Remap Sends Lawmakers Scrambling To New Homes|accessdate=2008-10-18|date=1991-10-06|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Plain Dealer (newspaper)|The Plain Dealer]]|author=Underwood, Jim and Thomas Suddes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dispatchpolitics.com/live/content/local_news/stories/2008/07/31/boechanges.ART_ART_07-31-08_B1_VRAT507.html?sid=101|title=New director will face first ballot in 3 months|accessdate=2008-10-18|date=2008-07-31|publisher=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|work=Dispatch Politics|author=Carmen, Barbara}}</ref> Unable to be elected in another district due to a one-year residency requirement, Cordray opted not to run for re-election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10E0D392EA30DB88&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=7 Presidential Hopefuls File For Primary|accessdate=2008-10-18|date=1992-02-21|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Curtin, Mike}}</ref> Instead, he decided to run for [[Ohio's 15th congressional district]] in the [[United States House of Representatives elections, 1992|1992 U.S. House of Representatives elections]], a seat being vacated by retiring thirteen-term Republican [[Chalmers Wylie]], and being challenged by Republican [[Deborah D. Pryce]]. 

Cordray won the Democratic nomination over Bill Buckel by a 18,731&ndash;5,329 (78&ndash;22%) margin,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10E0D41A9FF532B8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=U.S. House Democrat|accessdate=2008-10-19|date=1992-06-03|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]}}</ref> following the withdrawal of another candidate, Dave Sommer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10E0D3CC37C3AA50&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Democrat Pulls Out of the 15th Congressional District Race|accessdate=2008-10-19|date=1992-04-07|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10E0D3CF970DB008&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Democrats - Not GOP - To Battle For House in Primary|accessdate=2008-10-19|date=1992-04-04|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Curtin, Mike}}</ref> Cordray's platform included federal spending cuts, [[term limits]] for Congress and a [[line-item veto]] for the president.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10E0D40F56E1E130&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Candidates' Name Recognition Might Win In Primary Tuesday|accessdate=2008-10-19|date=1992-05-27|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Bradshaw, James}}</ref> When Pryce announced that she would vote to support [[abortion]] rights, Linda S. Reidelbach entered the race as an independent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10E0D416A446E550&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Conservative Jumps Into 15th House District Race|accessdate=2008-10-19|date=1992-06-02|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Curtin, Mike}}</ref> Thus, the general election was a three-way affair, with Pryce taking a [[Plurality (voting)|plurality]] of 110,390 votes (44.1%), Cordray taking 94,907 votes (37.9%) and Linda Reidelbach taking 44,906 votes (17.9%).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/1992election.pdf|title=Statistics of the Congressional Election of November 3, 1992|accessdate=2008-10-16|date=1993-05-31|publisher=U. S. Government Printing Office|author=Dendy, Dallas L., Jr.}}</ref>

===Law career===
While in private practice in 1993, Cordray co-wrote a [[legal brief]] for the [[Anti-Defamation League]], in a campaign supported by Ohio's attorney general, for the reinstatement of Ohio's [[hate crime]] laws.  This was considered by the U.S. Supreme Court, but not ruled on because of its similarity to a previous Wisconsin ruling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10E0DA52E6B3F580&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Ohio's Justices Asked to Reinstate Hate-Crimes Law|accessdate=2008-10-19|date=1993-09-12|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Bradshaw, James}}</ref>

In 1993 the [[government of Ohio]] created the office of state solicitor general to handle the state's appellate work. The state solicitor, appointed by the Ohio attorney general, is responsible for cases that are to be argued before the [[Ohio Supreme Court]] and the United States Supreme Court. Until 1998, the Solicitor worked without any support staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ohiobar.org/pubs/secnewslet/index.asp?section=Litigation&Issue=10;1&ID=665|title=State solicitor: An appellate lawyer<U+2019>s dream|accessdate=2008-10-16|date=Spring 2003|publisher=Ohio State Bar Association|work=Ohio State Bar Association Section Newsletters|author=Gormley, David M.}}</ref> Cordray, who had earlier worked for a summer in the office of the [[United States Solicitor General|United States solicitor general]],<ref name=FASG>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CPDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F80775E9D40AFDF&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Fisher Appoints Solicitor General|accessdate=2008-12-14|date=1993-09-19|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Plain Dealer (newspaper)|The Plain Dealer]]|author=Suddes, Thomas}}</ref> was the first Solicitor to be appointed, in September 1993.<ref name=FASG/> He held the position until he resigned after Ohio Attorney General [[Lee Fisher]] was defeated by [[Betty Montgomery]] in 1994.<ref name=TUSC>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/washington/stories/2000/12/18/focus5.html|title=The U.S. Supreme Court: making a lawyer's career|accessdate=2008-10-16|date=2000-12-15|publisher=American City Business Journals, Inc.|work=Business First of Columbus|author=Buchanan, Doug}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10E07D5B2669A9F8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=New Solicitor General Named By Montgomery - Jeffrey S. Sutton|accessdate=2008-10-19|date=1995-04-19|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]}}</ref> His cases before the Supreme Court included ''Wilson v. Layne'' ({{ussc|526|603|1999}}) and ''Hanlon v. Berger'' ({{ussc|526|808|1999}}).<ref name=FBfRC/> Though he lost his first case, he won his second case, which garnered a substantial amount of media attention for its consideration of the constitutionality of media ride-alongs with police.<ref name=TUSC/> Other cases included ''Household Credit Services v. Pfennig'' ({{ussc|541|232|2004}}), ''Brown v. Legal Foundation of Washington'' ({{ussc|538|216|2003}}), ''Demore v. Kim'' ({{ussc|538|510|2003}}), and ''Groh v. Ramirez'' ({{ussc|540|551|2004}}).

Cordray contested the [[Ku Klux Klan]]'s right to erect a cross at the [[Ohio Statehouse]] after the state's Capitol Square Review and Advisory Board denied the Klan's request during the 1993 Christmas holiday. He argued that the symbolic meaning of the cross was different from the [[Christmas tree]] and [[Menorah (Hanukkah)|menorah]], which the state permits. The Klan prevailed in the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on December 21, 1993, and erected a 10-foot (3&nbsp;m) cross the following day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10E0DACFE0B58900&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Klan May Raise Cross, Judge Rules|accessdate=2008-10-19|date=1993-12-22|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Edwards, Randall}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:ABJB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB62FEFCEA9BFC2&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Judge OKS New Cross By Klan Display To Be Erected Outside Statehouse|accessdate=2008-10-19|date=1993-12-22|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Akron Beacon Journal]]}}</ref> The same board denied the Klan a permit to rally on [[Martin Luther King Day]] (January 15, 1994) due to the group's failure to pay a $15,116 bill from its Oct. 23 rally and its refusal to post a bond to cover expenses for the proposed rally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:ABJB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB62FF59399D75B&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=State Stops Klan Rally On King's Birthday Board Cites Unpaid Bill For Earlier Event, Plus Concern For Public Safety|accessdate=2008-10-19|date=1994-01-07|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Plain Dealer (newspaper)|The Plain Dealer]]}}</ref> When the same 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals overturned the decision to deny the 1994 permit, the state chose not to appeal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CPDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F807C33C868C2E3&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=State Won't Appeal KKK Holiday Rally|accessdate=2008-10-19|date=1994-01-07|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Plain Dealer (newspaper)|The Plain Dealer]]}}</ref> The following year the Klan again applied to erect a cross for the Christmas holiday season, and the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals concurred with the prior ruling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10E081C85D311D30&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=KKK Wins Round in Statehouse Cross Dispute|accessdate=2008-10-19|date=1994-07-26|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Edwards, Randall}}</ref> The United States Supreme Court did not agree to hear arguments on the topic until a few weeks after Cordray resigned from his solicitor general position.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10E07CE5EE3B6748&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=High Court Takes KKK Cross Case - U.S. Justices Expected to Decide By July on Statehous Display|accessdate=2008-10-19|date=1995-01-14|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Lowe, Roger K.}}</ref> After his resignation in 1994 he several times represented the federal government in the U.S. Supreme Court: two of Cordray's appearances before were by appointment of the Democratic [[Bill Clinton]] [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]] and two were by the Republican [[George W. Bush]] Justice Department.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cordrayforohio.com/about/biography.html|title=Richard Cordray|accessdate=2008-12-14|publisher=The Cordray Committee}}</ref>

Cordray was granted a ruling by the Ohio Supreme Court that lower courts could not grant a [[stay of execution]] for a [[death row]] inmate. At the same time, Fisher, Cordray's boss, sought a [[referendum]] to mandate that appeals in death penalty cases be made directly to the Supreme Court.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:ABJB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB630EA99AF546B&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Death-Row Appeals Cut Off \ Ohio Supreme Court Bars Lower Courts From Stopping The Process For Inmates Due For Execution. Public Defender Says They'll Just Turn To Federal Courts For Relief.|accessdate=2008-10-19|date=1994-09-29|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Akron Beacon Journal]]|author=Snell, Roger}}</ref> In 1994 the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in ''Steffen v. Tate'' (39 F.3d 622 1994) limited death row inmates to a single federal appeal and said that federal courts cannot stay an execution if the case is still in a state court.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CPDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F807DCA867E21D2&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Court Limits Delay In Ohio Executions Death Row Inmates Will Now Get Only One Federal Appeal|accessdate=2008-10-19|date=1994-10-25|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Plain Dealer (newspaper)|The Plain Dealer]]|author=Sloat, Bill}}</ref>

===Late 20th century campaigns===
In early 1996, Cordray was elected to the [[Ohio Democratic Party]] Central Committee from the 15th district by a 5,472&ndash;1,718 margin over John J. Kulewicz.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DF8A2116946540&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Election Results|accessdate=2008-10-19|date=1996-03-20|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]}}</ref> In late 1996 Cordray, who was in private practice at the time, was a leading contender and finalist for a [[United States Attorney]] position during the second term of the [[Clinton Administration]], along with [[Kent Markus]] and [[Sharon Zealey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DF8B478FDEF148&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=White House To Fill Two Vacancies Here - Judge, U.S. Attorney|accessdate=2008-10-19|date=1996-11-09|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Ruth, Robert}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CPDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F80C4E00FF79BE4&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=3 Former Fisher Staffers On List For U.S. Attorney Post|accessdate=2008-10-19|date=1997-01-04|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Plain Dealer (newspaper)|The Plain Dealer]]}}</ref> Zealey was eventually selected.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CPDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F80C4E4EE80C442&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Ex-Fisher Aide Zealey Picked For Prosecutor|accessdate=2008-10-19|date=1997-01-09|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Plain Dealer (newspaper)|The Plain Dealer]]|author=Diemer, Tom}}</ref>

During the 1998 [[Ohio Attorney General elections|election for Ohio attorney general]], Cordray ran unopposed in the Democratic primary<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DE42318D16AD70&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Statewide Returns|accessdate=2008-10-19|date=1998-05-06|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]}}</ref> but was defeated, 62%&ndash;38%, by one-term Republican incumbent Betty Montgomery.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=950DE1DE143EF931A15754C0A96F958260|title=Political Briefing; A Run for the Senate, Or a Brawl for It?|accessdate=2008-10-15|date=1999-07-22|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Ayers, B. Drummond, Jr.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CPDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F80D0BE8639318D&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=GOP Stays In Charge of State Offices|accessdate=2008-10-19|date=1998-05-06|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Plain Dealer (newspaper)|The Plain Dealer]]|author=Suddes, Thomas and Mark Tatge}}</ref> In 2000 Cordray entered the [[United States Senate elections, 2000|U.S. Senate elections]] in a race that began as a three-way contest for the Democratic nomination to oppose first-term Republican incumbent [[Mike DeWine]]. The three-way race was unusual since the three candidates (Cordray, Rev. Marvin McMickle, and [[Ted Celeste]]) were encouraged to campaign together in order to promote name recognition, conserve resources and lessen infighting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CPDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F80D94A3B0968C6&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Democrat Senate Hopefuls Consider United Campaign|accessdate=2008-10-20|date=1999-11-12|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Plain Dealer (newspaper)|The Plain Dealer]]|author=McCarty, James F.}}</ref> Ohio Democratic party leaders believed Cordray was better suited for an Ohio Supreme Court seat and urged him to drop out of the Senate race.  Despite the Ohio Democrats not endorsing any candidate in the primary election,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DD407145882728&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=State Democrats Switch Players Late in The Game - Ohio Supreme Court Endorsement|accessdate=2008-10-20|date=1999-12-12|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Hallett, Joe}}</ref> the entry of Dan Radakovich as a fourth competitor,<ref name=FTVFSIPCNWKTV>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CPDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F80DAD1979DA0C4&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Four To Vie For Senate In Primary Challengers Not Well Known To Voters|accessdate=2008-10-20|date=2000-01-08|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Plain Dealer (newspaper)|The Plain Dealer]]|author=McCarty, James F.}}</ref> and the anticipated entry of former [[Mayor of Cincinnati]] and television personality [[Jerry Springer]], Cordray persisted in his campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CEQB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FC708AB62AF0E42&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Springer race wasn't meant to be|accessdate=2008-10-20|date=1999-08-15|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]]|author=Wilkinson, Howard}}</ref> Celeste, the younger brother of former Ohio governor [[Dick Celeste]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:TOBB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EAF38D7203692E9&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Decent Race Ahead|accessdate=2008-10-20|date=2000-03-10|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Toledo Blade]]}}</ref> won with 369,772 votes. He was trailed by McMickle (the only black Senate candidate in the country in 2000)<ref name=FTVFSIPCNWKTV/> with 204,811 votes, Cordray with 200,157, and Radakovich with 69,002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:DDNB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F51F2FFCA90D21F&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Tuesday's Ohio Election Results|accessdate=2008-10-20|date=2000-03-09|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Dayton Daily News]]}}</ref>

===Treasurer career===
Cordray was unopposed in the May 7, 2002, primary election for the Democratic nomination as Franklin County treasurer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DC84F96BA5C078&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Statewide and Franklin County Election Returns|accessdate=2008-10-20|date=2002-05-08|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]}}</ref> He defeated Republican incumbent Wade Steen, who had been appointed in May 2001 to replace Bobbie M. Hall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DC863D68AA2418&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Cordray Finally Pulls Off Victory|accessdate=2008-10-20|date=2002-11-06|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Woods, Jim and Mark Ferenchik}}</ref> The election was close, unofficially 131,199<U+2013>128,677 (50.5%<U+2013>49.5%), official margin of victory 3,232.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DC863E30134040&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Election 2002|accessdate=2008-10-20|date=2002-11-06|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DC86595757A1B8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=It's Official -- Cordray Wins Treasurer's Race - Ousted Republican Steen lost office by about 3,200 votes, final tally shows|accessdate=2008-10-20|date=2002-11-06|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Woods, Jim}}</ref> Cordray was the first Democrat to hold the position since 1977,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DC8646653089D0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Treasurer's Office Workers Await Word On Their Future|accessdate=2008-10-20|date=2002-11-11|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Woods, Jim}}</ref> and he assumed office on December 9, 2002, instead of after January 1 because he was filling Hall's unexpired term.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DC866641941550&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Cordray To Take Post Dec. 9 As New County Treasurer|accessdate=2008-10-20|date=2002-11-29|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Woods, Jim}}</ref>

In the 2004 race for re-election, the Franklin County Republican party made no endorsement,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DC8BA496D6B9B8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Some County Contests To Be 1-Horse Races|accessdate=2008-10-20|date=2003-12-31|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Woods, Jim}}</ref> but Republican Jim Timko challenged Cordray.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DADD1DF2D57D20&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=No Contest - Most Franklin County races unopposed, denying voters a voice|accessdate=2008-10-20|date=2004-01-10|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]}}</ref> Cordray defeated him and was elected to a four-year term by a 272,593<U+2013>153,625 (64%&ndash;36%) margin.<ref name=Ctrast>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/columbus/stories/2007/01/08/daily5.html|title=Cordray takes reins as state treasurer|accessdate=2008-10-15|date=2007-01-07|publisher=American City Business Journals, Inc.|work=Business First of Columbus|author=Ghani, Saleha N.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DADEF40AA39E18&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Election 2004 Part 1 of 3|accessdate=2008-10-20|date=2004-11-03|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]}}</ref> As Franklin County treasurer, Cordray focused on four major initiatives: collection of delinquent tax revenue through a tax lien certificate sale, creation of a land bank, personal finance education, and the development of a community outreach program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:ABJB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=11493506AABD9AC8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0d0cb579a3bda420|title=For Ohio Treasurer - We Recommend The Election of Richard Cordray|accessdate=2008-12-15|date=2006-10-03|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Akron Beacon Journal]]}}</ref> He managed a portfolio that averages $650 million and consistently beat its benchmarks, and he set new records for delinquent tax collection in Franklin County, which was the only Ohio county with a AAA [[credit rating]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:MNJB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=114BDF552BFCAE60&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0d0cb579a3bda420|title=Cordray tells Dems as treasurer he's been innovative, careful |accessdate=2008-12-15|date=2006-10-12|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Mansfield News Journal]]|author=Martz, Linda}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:DDNB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=114DB62D865B03A0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0d0cb579a3bda420|title=Candidates tout experience at debate|accessdate=2008-12-15|date=2006-10-18|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Dayton Daily News]]|author=Bischoff, Laura A.}}</ref> He also served as president of the Board of Revision and chair of the Budget Commission.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.21stcenturydems.org/candidates/profiles/richard-cordray|title=Richard Cordray|accessdate=2008-12-15|publisher=21st Century Democrats}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smartvoter.org/2006/05/02/oh/state/race/ohtrd/|title=Treasurer of State; State of Ohio; Democratic Party Voter Information|accessdate=2008-12-15|date=2006-05-02|publisher=League of Women Voters of California Education Fund}}</ref> In 2005, Cordray was named the national "County Leader of the Year" by ''[[American City & County]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CPDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10C448BF0CB7FB40&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Franklin County treasurer to seek state post|accessdate=2008-10-20|date=2005-08-26|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Plain Dealer (newspaper)|The Plain Dealer]]|author=Theis, Sandy}}</ref>

In the 2006 Democratic party primary election for state treasurer he was set to face [[Montgomery County, Ohio|Montgomery County]] Treasurer Hugh Quill who filed an entry,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:DDNB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10FF31D89FE47590&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Filings reveal tough court, treasury races - Familiar names to face off in May, November|accessdate=2008-10-20|date=2006-02-17|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Dayton Daily News]]|author=Bebbington, Jim}}</ref> but in the end, he was unopposed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=11163816070316F8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Bradley upset in primary - Treasurer derailed by unendorsed Republican|accessdate=2008-10-20|date=2006-05-03|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Nash, James and Catherine Candisky}}</ref> He defeated Republican nominee Sandra O'Brien for state treasurer in the 2006 election.  Cordray succeeded [[Jennette Bradley]] in a near-statewide sweep by the Democratic Party.<ref name=Ctrast/> Cordray noted that when he assumed statewide office, Ohio was challenged with restoring  public trust after the misdeeds of former [[List of Governors of Ohio|Ohio Governor]] [[Bob Taft]]. Referring to what in a similar way  would be required to follow Ohio Attorney General Marc Dann and his interim successor Nancy Rogers he said: "... we have been patiently rebuilding the public trust there [in the state government] and I think it would be a very similar task there in the Attorney General<U+2019>s office."<ref name=PRCAC/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1129553,00.html|title=Bob Taft <nowiki>|</nowiki> Ohio|accessdate=2008-10-15|date=2005-11-13|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|author=Cole, Wendy}}</ref>

===Attorney General race===
[[File:20081013 Richard Cordray.jpg|thumb|Cordray campaigning for [[Barack Obama]] on October 13, 2008 in {{city-state|Columbus|Ohio}}]]
Cordray announced his 2008 candidacy for Ohio state attorney general on June 11, 2008. He was endorsed by Ohio Governor [[Ted Strickland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/columbus/stories/2008/06/09/daily19.html|title=Cordray running for AG, backed by Strickland|accessdate=2008-10-15|date=2008-06-11|publisher=American City Business Journals, Inc.|work=Business First of Columbus|author=Burns, Matt}}</ref><ref name=Cmio>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=121454AFF3BF21A0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Cordray makes it official: He's running for AG - Strickland endorses him as GOP attacks|accessdate=2008-10-21|date=2008-06-12|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Nash, James}}</ref> The vacancy in the office of the attorney general was created by the May 14, 2008, resignation of [[Marc Dann]] who was embroiled in a sex scandal.<ref name=Cmio/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/cincinnati/stories/2008/08/04/editorial2.html|title=No joke, Mallory would be great|accessdate=2008-10-16|date=2008-08-01|publisher=American City Business Journals, Inc.|work=Business First of Columbus|author=Burns, Matt}}</ref><ref name=Olsdinag>{{cite web|url=http://www.dispatch.com/live/content/local_news/stories/2008/05/28/new_ag.html?sid=101|title=OSU law school dean is new attorney general: Nancy Hardin Rogers replaces Marc Dann|accessdate=2008-10-17|date=2008-05-28|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Niquette, Mark and Jim Siegel}}</ref> Several leading Republican party contenders such as Montgomery, [[Jim Petro]], DeWine, [[Maureen O'Connor]], and [[Rob Portman]] declined to enter the race.<ref name=Cmio/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=1219EE6BE7EA1BF0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Dearth of attorney general candidates highlights Ohio GOP's ills|accessdate=2008-10-21|date=2008-06-29|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Hallett, Joe}}</ref> Cordray's opponents in the race were [[Michael Crites]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]), and [[Robert M. Owens]] ([[independent politician|Independent]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dispatchpolitics.com/live/content/local_news/stories/2008/10/15/copy/TRIO.ART_ART_10-15-08_B5_BEBJUJ3.html?adsec=politics&sid=101|title=Attorney-general debate gets contentious quickly: 3 candidates bicker over campaign fundraising, ties to lawyers, criminal cases|accessdate=2008-10-17|date=2008-10-15|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Nash, James}}</ref> Cordray had a large financial advantage over his opponents with approximately 30 times as much campaign financing as Crites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=123058D02E4CB8E0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=AG fundraising gap widens - Cordray amasses $2.2 million; Crites, with $75,000, is upbeat|accessdate=2008-10-21|date=2008-09-05|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Nash, James}}</ref> Crites' campaign strategies included attempts to link Cordray with Dann<U+2014>an association the ''[[The Columbus Dispatch]]'' called into question<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=122F5B696E508970&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Cordray, Dann find little in common - There's little proof to back GOP claims of a close bond|accessdate=2008-10-21|date=2008-09-02|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Nash, James}}</ref><U+2014>and promoting himself as having more years of prosecutorial experience.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=1222D509AD7F7DD0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420 | title=Worthy opponents - The candidates for Ohio attorney general should keep campaign on high road|accessdate=2008-10-21 | date=2008-07-26 | publisher=[[Newsbank]] | work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]] }}</ref> Cordray asserted that he managed the state's money safely despite the turbulence of the [[financial crisis of 2007<U+2013>2008]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=123D337A0BAC3860&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=AG rivals tangle on tactics - Attorney general candidates duel over reining in Wall St., lenders|accessdate=2008-10-21|date=2008-10-14|publisher=[[Newsbank]] | work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Nash, James}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12393ECB54A2DA28&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Cordray: Ohio's money safe - Most invested in short-term bonds, treasurer says | accessdate=2008-10-21 | date=2008-10-02 | publisher=[[Newsbank]] | work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Johnson, Alan}}</ref>

Ohio statewide offices are regularly contested every four years in the [[United States midterm election|midterm election]] years. 2008 is [[Classes of United States Senators|Class 2]] senatorial election year, and Ohio is a state with class 1 and class 3 senators. Thus, the Attorney General race was the only non-presidential statewide race in the 2008 election aside from contests for two seats on the Ohio Supreme Court.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ohiodems.org/site/c.mhLRKZPCLmF/b.3817745/k.F573/Judicial_Candidates.htm|title=Judicial Candidates: Supreme Court Candidates|accessdate=2008-10-16|publisher=Ohio Democratic Party}}</ref>  Cordray garnered 56.74% of the vote, while his challengers, Republican Mike Crites and Independent Robert Owens, received 38.43% and 4.83%, respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sos.state.oh.us/SOS/elections/electResultsMain/2008ElectionResults/attGen110408.aspx|title=Ohio Attorney General - Unexpired Term Ending January 9, 2011: November 4, 2008|accessdate=December 28, 2008 |publisher=[[Ohio Secretary of State]]|work=www.sos.state.oh.us}}</ref>

==Personal==
[[File:1987-04-22Jeopardy!Podiums1.jpg|thumb|left|Cordray (first podium at left) in 1987 on ''[[Jeopardy!]]'']]
Cordray was born in {{city-state|Columbus|Ohio}},<ref name=PRCAC>{{cite web|url=http://www.whiotv.com/politics/17067462/detail.html|title=Profile: Richard Cordray, AG Candidate|accessdate=2008-10-15|date=2008-08-01|publisher=[[WHIO-TV]]|author=Otte, Jim}}</ref> the middle child between brothers Frank, Jr. and Jim.<ref name=FBfRC/> He was married in 1992 to Margaret "Peggy" Cordray,<ref name=FBfRC/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:TOBB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EAF3A7C39447EFB&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Cordray to Run For Attorney General|accessdate=2008-10-17|date=1997-06-24|publisher=Newsbank|work=[[The Blade (newspaper)|The Blade]]}}</ref> a law professor at [[Capital University Law School]]. The Cordrays have twins, a daughter and son,  and currently reside near [[Grove City, Ohio]].<ref name=PRCAC/> Cordray's father, Frank Cordray, Sr., was living in Grove City at the time Cordray moved back to Columbus to work for the law firm of Jones Day.<ref name=STCLFLTHCCIRC/><ref name=1SLTTOoO/>  His father retired as an Orient Developmental Center  program director for mentally retarded residents after 43 years of service.<ref name=FBfRC/> His mother, from [[Dayton, Ohio]],<ref name=PRCAC/> died in 1980.<ref name=FBfRC/><ref name=STCLFLTHCCIRC/>  She had been a social worker, teacher and founder of Ohio's first foster grandparent program for individuals with mental disabilities.<ref name=FBfRC/>

Cordray has the distinction of being an undefeated five-time champion and [[Jeopardy! Tournament of Champions|Tournament of Champions]] semifinalist on ''[[Jeopardy!]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DE42CD1E7AEEC8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0d0cb579a3bda420|title=Democrat - Public Service Where Cordray Wants To Be|accessdate=2008-12-16|date=1998-08-30|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Candisky, Catherine}}</ref> In 1987, he won $45,303 from the show, which he used to pay law school debt, to pay taxes and to buy a used car.<ref name=JSSHGFHO>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10E0D420EBC202D8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title='Jeopardy!' Star Says He's Game For Higher Office|accessdate=2008-10-19|date=1992-06-09|publisher=Newsbank|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Keller, Julia}}</ref> The total winnings came from $40,303 in prize money during his five-contest streak and $5,000 for a first round win on the Tournament of Champions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DADE47F04E2660&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title='Jeopardy!' Has Cordray Playing Along|accessdate=2008-10-17|date=2004-07-16|publisher=Newsbank|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Vitale, Robert}}</ref> His campaign for public office in 1990 precluded him from participating in the ''[[Super Jeopardy!]]'' elimination tournament of champions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=11B8688ECFDD3BC8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Candidacy Cancels Shot on 'Jeopardy!'|accessdate=2008-10-17|date=1990-07-09|publisher=Newsbank|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Willey, Jack}}</ref> [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], the network that carried the show, had a policy against political contestants for the show (excluding ''[[Celebrity Jeopardy!]]'').<ref name=JSSHGFHO/> Cordray carried the [[Olympic Flame]] through {{city-state|Findlay|Ohio}}, as part of the nationwide torch relay to the [[1996 Summer Olympics]] in {{city-state|Atlanta|Georgia}}.<ref name=FBfRC/>  He has served as a member of the Advisory Board for the Friends of the Homeless and part of [[Al Gore]]'s select group known as Leadership '98.<ref name=FBfRC/>

